06879nam a22009135i 9780748627080DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222006stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486270807 a10.1515/97807486270802doi  a(DE-B1597)616633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0000002bisacsh  aCI 5599qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/18484:1 aFuglsang, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeleuze and the Social /cMartin Fuglsang, Bent Meier Sorensen. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDeleuze Connections : DECO00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Deleuze and the Social: Is there a D-function? 1 -- tPart I Order and Organisation -- tChapter 1 Order, Exteriority and Flat Multiplicities in the Social -- tChapter 2 The Trembling Organisation: Order, Change and the Philosophy of the Virtual -- tChapter 3 The Others of Hierarchy: Rhizomatics of Organising -- tPart II Subjectivity and Transformation -- tChapter 4 In the Mean Time: Vitalism, Affects and Metamorphosis in Organisational Change -- tChapter 5 I Knew there were Kisses in the Air -- tChapter 6 Becoming-Cyborg: Changing the Subject of the Social? -- tPart III Art and the Outside -- tChapter 7 Practical Deleuzism and Postmodern Space -- tChapter 8 Anti-Oedipus – Thirty Years On (Between Art and Politics) -- tPart IV Capitalism and Resistance -- tChapter 9 Capitalism and Resistance The Concepts of Life and the Living in the Societies of Control -- tChapter 10 Nomad Citizenship and Global Democracy -- tChapter 11 Deleuze, Change, History -- tPart V Social Constitution and Ontology -- tChapter 12 Society with/out Organs -- tChapter 13 Deleuzian Social Ontology and Assemblage Theory -- tNotes on contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first book to focus on the implications of Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari's thinking on the social sciences and organisationThis book is concerned with the most basic notions of 'the social'. It seeks both to comprehend the 'multiplicity' of the social - in Deleuzian terms, the 'becoming' of the social itself; and it seeks to develop a new social analytical practice. Each of the newly commissioned chapters aims to show the strength of as well as practice the radicalism of a Deleuzian and Guattarian approach to social science and organisation studies. Deleuze and the Social is a book about order, subjectivity, art, capitalism and the construction of a social ontology. It avoids scholasticism by foregrounding its authors' shared concern for practical issues. How is social order constituted? How is resistance possible between the rush of capitalism and the overcoding of the State? How are thinking and living possible? Deleuze and the Social raises these questions and many more.The international team of authors includes Eric Alliez, Maurizio Lazzarato, Eugene Holland, Paul Patton, Manuel DeLanda and Ian Buchanan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAlbertsen, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlliez, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBay, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBos, Renéten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLanda, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiken, Bülent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.